text_answer.content:
This passage has 'ok boomer' energy.
While the question of how long digital archives last is still true, especially as older technologies are phased out and become inaccessible, it's not really fair to say that photographs are universally more durable. They're still subject to physical damage and decay that has lead to much of photographed history getting lost. This is a clear example of survivor bias - where we judge the validity of something based on what has survived without taking into consideration of what's potentially been lost. (This is also an extension of the 'ok boomer' note above).
